content:
One risk we run here is doubling down on one tenet of SJD (whether we realize it or not) in order to highlight the harm of another.
Let&rsquo;s call this the &ldquo;Master&rsquo;s Tools Dilemma&rdquo; of SJD.
   ESSAY: The Master&rsquo;s Tools Will Never Dismantle the Master&rsquo;s House / Audre Lorde   If you haven&rsquo;t read this essay by Audre Lorde, we can&rsquo;t recommend it enough. Here&rsquo;s the main quote we&rsquo;re pulling (the same one that always gets pulled):
 &ldquo;For the master&rsquo;s tools will never dismantle the master&rsquo;s house. They may allow us temporarily to beat him at his own game, but they will never enable us to bring about genuine change.&rdquo;
 We need avoid wielding one tenet of SJD to dismantle another. Want to discuss this article? Or the this idea in general? Head over to the community.
Then let&rsquo;s take this one step further&hellip;

We asked you in the beginning of Module 1 to share what SJD-related thoughts you had on your mind (if you didn&rsquo;t reply, it&rsquo;s not too late: here&rsquo;s the form).
Here are some of the themes we saw in your replies:
   &ldquo;Toxic call out culture&rdquo; as a celebrated tactic   &ldquo;Fighting oppression of one group by accepting oppression of another.&rdquo;   &ldquo;Advocat[ing] for justice to be achieved on [a particular person&rsquo;s] own terms&rdquo; and only their terms   &ldquo;Reacting negatively to differing perspectives being shared without exploring why that person may have that perspective&rdquo;

Our ability to define SJD, to spot it, to name it, the codex &ndash; really, all of this stuff &ndash; is a work in progress. Just like us.
Even as you continue into Modules 3, 4, 5, and 6, it&rsquo;s okay to keep circling back to what we covered here. And what we covered in &ldquo;Dot-Com-Munity.&rdquo;
In fact, as a stance, we&rsquo;re super pro-circling (not in a dogmatic way). The Module 2 Community is here for you whenever something pops into mind.
